    correctAnswer: 'B',
    explanation: 'Choice B is correct. Hexokinase I has Km ≈ 0.1 mM — it is essentially saturated at fasting portal glucose (5 mM >> 0.1 mM) and cannot respond to further glucose increases. Glucokinase has Km ≈ 10 mM — at fasting glucose (5 mM = 0.5 × Km), it operates at approximately 33% of Vmax (Michaelis-Menten: v = Vmax × 5/(10+5) = Vmax/3). At postprandial 15 mM: v = Vmax × 15/25 = 60% Vmax. This proportional response allows glucokinase to increase its rate as portal glucose rises, functioning as a glucose dosimeter that buffers postprandial hyperglycemia. Additionally, glucokinase is not feedback-inhibited by glucose-6-phosphate (unlike hexokinase I), allowing continued phosphorylation at high glucose.',
